[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4 {Welcome to my course on the Italian!  The Italian is one of the most popular openings in modern chess right now. It has seen a huge boost in popularity since 2016 and it has become a staple in every top event. Why is that the case? One of the initial causes was that many White players could not get any edge in the solid variations of the Ruy Lopez such as the Berlin, Open, or Marshall. So people started exploring the Italian in more detail. They then discovered that the a4 setups were quite venomous against the conventional main lines for Black.  Nearly all the elite GMs swiftly embraced it, and over the past decade, the theory has developed exponentially. Many of these subtleties are still limited to the GM level and I firmly believe that it should be accessible to all players. Understanding these positions would tremendously improve your general chess knowledge and hopefully, also give you great results  I have been a 1.e4 player throughout my career for over 12 years. Since 2019, I have been playing the Italian almost exclusively in most of my games. I completely fell in love with the structure and the nuances in the positions. I have had great results with the Italian, and more importantly, I feel very comfortable in the resulting positions.  Many people have this misconception that the Italian is played only by lazy people who do not want to study openings. This is very far from the truth. I have always been someone who works a lot on his openings - maybe even too much! And when I started studying the Italian, I was amazed at the number of details and intricacies involved in the system. I read several books and studied countless games between strong players over a long period before I started playing the Italian confidently. This is because there was no clear guide or manual explaining all the different concepts involved in the opening. Even the very top players spent a lot of time on their opening moves in the Italian, as every different system has its unique features.  I have always been studying top-level games and updating my files and knowledge about the latest developments. I recently decided that I would be taking a break from competitive chess for the next few years. This is the perfect time for me to share all my ideas and knowledge about the Italian as I do not need to be worried about revealing my preparation. As it is, I am recommending all of my main lines, which I have been playing over the last four years.  I have done a lot of work on this course over the past few months, using the latest cloud engines, correspondence, and engine games. But more than everything, I have focused on recommending sound, practical lines that will pose the maximum problems for Black. I do not go for crazy computer lines, which will require us to remember a lot of variations. My aim has always been to find the right balance between critical lines and a compact repertoire. Our initial moves remain very similar across all the lines, and we will tailor our plans based on Black's setup. I have tried my best to explain the advantages and drawbacks of every system that Black can choose.  In modern chess, it is almost impossible for anyone to get a clear advantage straight out of the opening unless Black makes some inaccuracies, especially when Black goes for the solid 1...e5. It is just the nature of chess. But on the other hand, we can definitely strive to choose the kinds of positions where it is not easy for Black to find the best moves on the board. This is what we should be aiming for. I usually try to deviate from the deeply analyzed main lines at the right moment(not too early and not very deep into the main lines). I will then go on to analyze these positions pretty deeply and come up with new ideas and concepts.  Modern-day chess keeps evolving, with increasing importance given to rapid and blitz chess, both over the board and online. Here again, we have a big edge when we go for the Italian, as the importance of understanding is much higher than concrete lines. When the number of games we play increases, the need to have a dependable and trusted opening system also increases. It gives us the confidence to always be able to outplay our opponent, even if we forget the concrete details.  Some of the other things to note are that I will be objective in the evaluation of the variations. There are many cases where Black will equalize if he is able to make a series of good decisions. But even here, in most cases, the positions are still complex, and I will explain our plans clearly. I have gone through a lot of material on the Italian and I am recommending paths that are relatively new and unexplored in all the existing productions.  I hope that you will enjoy going through the course as much as I did making it. I am a frequent user of Chessable, and I will always be available to answer any questions or queries on the forum. Good luck!} 
