[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Brief History 5.c3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Bc5 {This is the starting position of the main Bc5 variation in the Italian. The bishop is more active here compared to e7. On the other hand, we can gain a few tempi on the queenside playing against the bishop on c5.} 
5. c3
5. d6
6. O-O
6. O-O {There are several options here for us. Traditionally, everyone used to go for the same setup with Bb3, Re1, Nbd2-f1-g3. Black players found numerous ways to equalize there- the simplest being the plan with a6, Ba7 followed by Be6. Even the structures with fxe6 were completely fine for Black as he was able to create play quicker on the kingside and the center.      Around the years 2015-16, White players discovered that it was a better version to go for a4 instead of Bb3. This way in the Be6 lines we save a tempo as a4 is a very useful move on the queenside. This was one of the main reasons behind the revival of the Italian at the very top level. Suddenly the traditional ways for Black to equalize were not working that well. This led to Black players going deeper and studying the Italian very seriously to try to find clear ways to equalize.     They improved upon the Be6 plan by going for Re8 first. But even here the rook was shaky on e6 and often ran into the d4 break. Many players tried to regroup the knight to g6 and go for the d5 break. White players started to deal with this by immediately gaining control over the center with the move d4. Next, they came up with the a5 systems. Here the same fxe6 structures work well for Black since he has a better grip over the queenside. However, this does weaken the b5 square which we will look to exploit.     People discovered that the Italian was a serious weapon for White and there was no clear way to completely equalize with Black. White also further expanded his tries with moves such as Bg5 which lead to messy positions. However, all of these nuances are still mostly limited to GM level or higher.      Many other players are confused by the endless move orders and get discouraged about learning the Italian. This is something that I want to change through this course. In addition to giving you concrete weapons against every Black alternative, I want to help you understand and enjoy the intricacies of the Italian. I believe that this will not only help you get great results in the Italian but will also tremendously improve your general chess understanding.} 
7. Re1 {This is the modern approach to the position. We wait for Black to go a6 and meet it with the move a4. The bishop remains on c4 and it can even come back directly to f1 in some cases.} 
7. a6
8. a4 {Our general rule is to always meet the move a6 with a4.} 
8. Ba7
9. h3
9. h6
10. Nbd2 {This is one of the main tabiyas in the Modern Italian. We will always meet Be6 by taking on e6 followed by the move b4, gaining space on the queenside.} 
