5. Nc3 {I came across this move around a year ago when I saw some top players using it very successfully. Since I played the Italian from both sides, I was very curious and studied it for a while. I felt it was interesting but did not think of it as a serious weapon for classical chess.     A few months later, I was working as a second for the Indian team at the Chess Olympiad, and we were playing the Uzbek team. While preparing against the talented youngster Sindarov Javokhir, I was really surprised to see him employ this move consistently in all his games. He had won two games just before our match playing this exact system. I analyzed it pretty deeply, and I discovered that it was not that easy for Black to equalize in all the lines.     It has become more popular since then and I have also used it in quite a few games. However, it is still vastly undervalued by most players, and we will use it to our advantage. Here our play is more aggressive compared to the main lines that we have seen so far. Since the position is very symmetrical,  we need to play very actively to pose problems for Black.     I am dividing this system into four chapters based on Black's 5th move and our subsequent plan. The positions are very different in each of these chapters. Also, I am structuring it in such a way that we look at the more critical lines first before moving on to some sidelines at the end. This is because it is important to first understand the main ideas behind this system.    So which system to choose in a tournament game? Generally, I suggest you start by learning the main c3, d3 lines. After you get a hang of those positions, you can add some variety with 5. Nc3. Alternatively, you can use the 5. Nc3 system as an effective blitz and rapid repertoire while you are learning the c3, d3 lines for classical chess. 5. Nc3 is easier to learn and understand but it may not help your general chess understanding as much as the main lines. At the end of the day, it also depends on which positions you prefer and are comfortable with.} 
5. d6 {This is the main move according to the number of games in the database, and it is very logical. However, the drawback is that it runs into-} 
6. Na4 {and we win the bishop. The resulting positions give us a slight edge and we will explore them in more detail here.} 
