 {I have been a frequent user of Chessable since the pandemic started in 2020. I am a huge fan of the Move Trainer technology which helps you understand and remember your openings better. I also really like the concept of being able to keep updating the course over the years as and when the theory develops. I feel that the Italian is the perfect opening to study on Chessable. There are several similar move orders which you can drill to make sure that you do not mix them up in your games. The tempo of going through a course on Chessable is gradual and that is absolutely the right approach for the Italian. It is more important to grasp all the ideas properly rather than go through the course extremely quickly.   I recommend you to first train the Practise your move orders chapter after the Introduction. This will give you an extended introduction to the main lines and also help you understand the various move orders. This is a chapter that you can always come back to whenever you are confused about the move orders.  After this, you can move on to the Quick Starter which is another feature that I really like. This is already enough to get a working knowledge of the Italian and to add it to your repertoire. If you do not have the luxury of time to go through the entire course, you can always use the remaining chapters as a reference database. Once you encounter a new idea from your opponent you can check out the corresponding chapter for more details.  If you do have more time, you can check out the rest of the course at your own pace to further improve your understanding of the Italian. I think that going through the entire course will definitely improve your general chess understanding and expose you to many new ideas.  I have designed the course in such a way that every chapter is independent of the other. So you can directly check out the chapters that you are most interested in. I have arranged the chapters starting from the sidelines on move 3. It is perfectly possible to begin studying the main lines first if you are already familiar with the Italian. If you are starting fresh then I recommend you to start with the sidelines and build up your knowledge before tackling the main lines. You can always address any queries that you might have in the forum discussions where I will be active.} 1. --
