1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4 {One of the distinctive features of the Modern Italian is the flexibility in the move order for both sides. There is a myriad of options to consider on each move. My aim through this course is to enable you to navigate these structures confidently based on your understanding. As White, we will go for the same move order and structure in most cases. We have a specific system of rules and guidelines that will help you to neutralize or exploit Black's move order. There is no scope for Black to 'trick' us by changing the move order.} 
3. Nf6 {I feel this is Black’s most flexible move order as he has a few decent options on move 4. To be honest I usually just hope that my opponents only go for the Bc5 move order as it does drastically cut down on the options I have to prepare for before a tournament game. The one clear drawback is that Black has to know the Ng5-variations well; otherwise, it can go bad quickly.} 
4. d3
4. h6 {This is a rather modern trend aiming to develop the bishop on g7. Usually Black goes for d6 followed by the move g5 gaining space on the kingside. It is a pretty serious system and one of the few areas where I do not have a great score. This is mainly because I was too lazy to properly prepare a clear weapon against this system. We will not do this mistake and I have devoted a lot of time to recommending a strong and practical setup to pose maximum problems.} 
5. O-O
5. d6
6. c3 {This is our approach to almost all the systems which Black can play. This is one of the biggest attractions of the Italian from the white side.} 
6. g5
7. Nbd2
7. Bg7
8. Bb3 {This is one of the very few cases where we go for Bb3 in the Modern Italian. Usually, we meet a6 with a4 and our bishop gets traded on e6 directly. Or we try to go for d4 directly and get our bishop to f1. Sometimes we even go to b5 with our bishop.   However here, we want to get our knight to c4 and e3 quickly, exploiting the f5-square that Black has weakened considerably. Since the Black bishop is on g7, ...d5 is a usual occurrence and we prepare for it in advance. We also have the option of meeting ...Be6 with Bc2 now.} 
