3. Nf6 {I feel this is Black’s most flexible move order as he has a few decent options on move 4. To be honest I usually just hope that my opponents only go for the Bc5 move order as it does drastically cut down on the options I have to prepare for before a tournament game. The one clear drawback is that Black has to know the Ng5-variations well; otherwise, it can go bad quickly.} 
4. d3
4. Bc5 {The starting position of the Modern Italian. The modern way of playing is characterized by the move a4 instead of the traditional Bb3 system. This is one of the main reasons behind the revival of the Italian. But one general rule to keep in mind- Do not play a4 unnecessarily before Black goes for the move a6.} 
5. c3
5. a6 {This is recommended by Jan Gustafsson in his course on Chessable. Both of us aim to reach the same position further down the line.} 
6. O-O {A good question here would be- why not go for our usual a4? This is a thumb rule which I have throughout this system. We almost always meet the move ...a6 with a4. However, another frequent idea that I keep repeating is always to play the most necessary move first. Here, O-O is more necessary and flexible since Black has not played d6, and we are already threatening to go for the d4 break. We can go a4 on the next move.} 
6. d6
7. a4 {The point of the Modern Italian. We stop ideas of Na5 and also gain space on the queenside. We wait for Black to go for Be6 when we can trade directly without losing a tempo on Bb3. Another idea is to go d4 and bring our bishop back directly to f1 strengthening our kingside.} 
7. O-O
8. Re1 {This transposes to the main move order in the Italian.} 
