[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4 {One of the distinctive features of the Modern Italian is the flexibility in the move order for both sides. There is a myriad of options to consider on each move. My aim through this course is to enable you to navigate these structures confidently based on your understanding. As White, we will go for the same move order and structure in most cases. We have a specific system of rules and guidelines that will help you to neutralize or exploit Black's move order. There is no scope for Black to 'trick' us by changing the move order.} 
3. Nf6 {I feel this is Black’s most flexible move order as he has a few decent options on move 4. To be honest I usually just hope that my opponents only go for the Bc5 move order as it does drastically cut down on the options I have to prepare for before a tournament game. The one clear drawback is that Black has to know the Ng5-variations well; otherwise, it can go bad quickly.} 
4. d3
4. Bc5 {The starting position of the Modern Italian. The modern way of playing is characterized by the move a4 instead of the traditional Bb3 system. This is one of the main reasons behind the revival of the Italian. But one general rule to keep in mind- Do not play a4 unnecessarily before Black goes for the move a6.} 
5. c3
5. d6 {This is the most common and logical move order.} 
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. Re1 {Usually in these positions we wait for Black to commit to a specific setup to choose our plan. And Re1 is a very useful and flexible waiting move. It prepares Nd2-f1-g3 and Be3 in some cases. It also helps us to go for the d4 break in the future.} 
7. Bb6 {This is one of the latest trends in the Italian. Black improves upon the traditional plan of a6, Ba7 followed by Ne7-g6 by directly going to b6. He will go for Ne7-g6 next and meet a4 with c6.} 
8. h3 {Once again we want to include h3 and h6. Here we usually wait for Black to take his knight to g6 before going for d4 in the center.} 
8. h6
9. Nbd2
9. Ne7
10. a4
