[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter Guide 4...d5"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6 {This is the most flexible way for Black, keeping many options open regarding the f8-bishop. The downside is that Black has to study the sharp lines after Ng5 quite deeply. I have played Ng5 a couple of times especially after studying Wesley's course. But it usually leads to complete equality if Black knows their stuff- something which is a constant worry. Also Black has several different ways to equalize there.   I have played the d3-lines in almost all my games and I think it is the most critical way to pose problems for Black. Also, it leads to positions where the understanding of the position is much more important, compared to concrete lines. I would recommend you to first try and grasp the most important ideas and nuances in the positions. Every different setup which Black chooses, will have some advantages and drawbacks- which you need to know at the back of your hand.} 
4. d3
4. d5 {Modern chess! This is a very serious and concrete idea that has not been deeply explored yet. I faced this in an over-the-board game in December 2022 and it was not at all easy to figure things out on the board. It has been taken up recently by many top players and I would not be surprised to see it become much more popular in the future. Black is trying to equalize by force- we cannot rely solely on our understanding here.} 
5. exd5
5. Nxd5
6. O-O
6. Be7 {The most natural move getting ready to castle and also protecting the king along the e-file from potential pins.} 
7. Re1
7. f6 {This is a critical position where White has a few interesting options to pose problems} 
8. h3
8. Nb6
9. Bb3 {Of course it is more important to stop Black from castling immediately. Black has to try to castle queenside now.} 
9. Bf5 {The better move order to go for Bf5 and now Black is willing to give up his bishop-pair in order to castle queenside.} 
10. d4 {Our usual idea breaking open the center but this time as a sacrifice. We really cannot allow Qd7 and O-O-O so easily.} 
10. a5 {Very precise. The inclusion of a5 and a4 helps Black considerably in the Nxd4-variations. White's queen will now get stuck on b7 in many lines without the escape route on a6. Deep!} 
11. a4 {Here we need to stop potential a4 irrespective of the b4-square.} 
11. Nxd4
12. Nxd4
12. Qxd4
13. Qf3 {At first sight this does look crushing for White. Black must have prepared his next move in advance.} 
13. Bd7
14. Nc3 {The position is pretty dangerous for Black. He has to keep playing very precisely. You can check out more details here.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter Guide 4...Be7 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Be7 {This is quite common across all levels. Usually, people go for this to avoid all the theory in the Bc5-lines and just get a solid playable position. It is important to note that the general guidelines here are a bit different from the main lines. We will go for a4 early and the main reason is that the structures with Bxe6, fxe6 are a better version for us as the Bishop on e7 is less active. In the main lines with Bc5 we go a4 only after Black goes for the move a6. Also, Nc3 setups are much more potent here, especially when Black tries to start play on the kingside with the move f5.} 
5. O-O
5. O-O
6. Re1 {White needs to stop the move d5.So far our plan is exactly the same as in the main lines. Re1 is a useful move in almost every version of the Italian. It creates a square on f1 for the knight and discourages the central break-d5.} 
6. d6
7. a4 {We create a luft for the bishop on a2. Black has many different options here. Our general guidelines are-   1) Stay flexible regarding the b1-knight until Black has shown his hand. Nc3-d5 is very effective if Black wants to play on the kingside. Also, unlike the main lines we do not want to go for c3 very early as we want the option to go for Nc3-d5. Black has to commit to some plan in the next couple of moves and we will react accordingly. We have a useful waiting move in h3 if needed.   2) We usually try to go for a5 and fix the pawn structure in our favour on the queenside. Different people go for different approaches- some like to play a5 and others want to keep options open. I feel going for a5 at the right moment makes a lot of sense- to gain space and also prepare the move Qb3.} 
7. Kh8 {Black is trying to improve upon the plan of h6, Nh7 by playing Kh8, Ng8, and f5 as quickly as possible. White has to play precisely} 
8. a5 {Again we include the moves a5 and a6 when we get a chance.} 
8. a6
9. h3 {A useful flexible move which is very common across the Italian. Moves such as Re1, h3 are generally always necessary at some point. We keep the knight on b1 flexible until Black fully commits to a plan. The second he plays Ng8 we are ready to jump with our knight to d5.} 
9. Ng8
10. Nc3 {Ok time to go to d5! The problem for Black is that compared to the KID White has a few extra tempi in the position.} 
10. f5
11. Nd5 {All our pieces are well placed and it is not easy to create anything for Black on the kingside. Also, we have a very cunning trap prepared.} 
11. fxe4
12. dxe4
12. Nf6
13. Qd2 {A nice idea that I wanted to illustrate- we prepare b4, creatively keeping the option of Ra3 open. You can check out more details here.} 
