[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter Guide 4...Bc5 6...d5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Bc5 {This is the starting position of the main lines in the Italian with the bishop on c5. It can arise from both 3...Nf6 and 3...Bc5 move orders. Black has a number of different setups here.} 
5. c3
5. O-O {Black is flexible regarding his d pawn, keeping options of both d6 and d5 open. One of the drawbacks is that Bg5 is more dangerous now compared to before Black castled, but it still leads to very messy positions with chances for both sides.   Black is threatening to go d5 and it is not very easy to stop. Playing Re1 allows Ng4 and after every other natural move, d5 is possible. We need to study this line carefully as it is very concrete and we cannot rely solely on concepts and ideas. Black players usually go for this to try and equalize directly.} 
6. O-O {We continue with our normal plan allowing d5. One of the things I like about this line for White is that Black has to be very well prepared and we have several ways to pose problems. In many lines, Black has to give up some material and he needs to know exactly how to prove his compensation.} 
6. d5
7. exd5
7. Nxd5 {This is a critical position in this system and we have a number of different options. We can go after the central pawn, play on the queenside or prevent the move Bg4. All of the moves have their own merits and demerits.} 
8. Re1 {This is the most natural and common move putting more pressure on the center. We should play quite energetically here as Black will be very comfortable once he bolsters his center.} 
8. Bg4 {This pin is quite annoying for White and h3, g4 will create a weakness on the kingside.} 
9. Nbd2 {We continue our development and if given time we will play h3, Nf1/e4-g3 and get a nice edge. The drawback is that after Nb6 the d3 pawn becomes an issue. But we cannot have everything in life.} 
9. Nb6
10. h3 {Including h3, Bh5 is in our favour usually as Black is forced to commit to one of the options. We are looking to time h3 at the right moment to limit Black's options.} 
10. Bh5
11. b4 {This is an old line that many people would be unfamiliar with. Bb3 and Bb5 are much more popular. We gain space on the queenside with tempo and also create a potential threat of b4-b5. My approach to opening preparation has always been to choose theoretically sound main lines, but then find my own way to pose problems. Rather than go deep into the main lines, it makes a lot of sense to force our opponent to think on his own, as early as possible.} 
11. Be7 {Keeping an eye on the d3 pawn. Already this is not an obvious decision if Black is not well prepared. Many players tend to underestimate slightly older lines and instead focus most of their time on the latest trends. We can utilize this to catch our opponents off guard.} 
12. Qe2 {This is a very rare idea in OTB chess. I played one of the two games here and it is actually quite unpleasant to meet with Black. It is very likely that Black is out of his prep and we are just starting. We are threatening to go Bb3 and also potentially g4 and Nf3-e5.} 
12. Nxc4 {Black has to get rid of the bishop when he can. Now if he is just able to consolidate, he might even take over. We need to act extremely dynamically in the center.} 
13. Nxc4 {We have ideas of b5 or g4 followed by winning the e5 pawn. Black has to make some concession. He does have the bishop pair though and so he can afford to even give up material at some point and get good compensation.} 
13. f6 {This is definitely what I would expect from my opponent. The problem for Black is that now his king is getting exposed.} 
14. b5
14. Nb8
15. d4 {We strike before Black can bring his knight back into the game. We will not hesitate to play g4 at the right moment. Black has to make a tough decision here. I have shown this position to a few of my GM friends and no one was able to equalize cleanly.} 
15. Qd5 {This is probably the most natural move and it happened in my game against IM Harikrishnan A.Ra. I ended up getting a huge time advantage in that game and won pretty convincingly.} 
16. Ne3
16. Qe6
17. dxe5
17. fxe5
18. Ng4 {We want to win the light-squared bishop even at the cost of a pawn. You can check out more details here.} 
