7. Re1
7. a5 {One of the two major approaches to the position. Black prevents us from gaining space on the queenside. Now the Bxe6 fxe6 structures are not so appealing to us- Black will usually equalise comfortably. This is actually my main repertoire with the Black pieces. Anish, as per his overall approach, goes for quick d4-lines which are again, probably not more than a one-game try. I do not want to go for the absolute main lines, but at the same time, I want to recommend something which is critical and can be played over a long period of time.} 
8. h3 {I believe the inclusion of h3 and h6 is in White's favour in most lines in the Italian and this is no exception. Black's idea in this line is to go for Be6 and after Bb5 go for Qb8-a7. But he cannot do that unless White goes for Nbd2 (since otherwise White will be able to get d4 after Qb8).} 
8. Be6
9. Bb5
9. Ba7 {This has been played recently by Anish in Tata Steel 2023 and also by Magnus in the CCT. Black avoids playing h6 and now he will go for Ne7-g6.} 
10. Be3 {We will be gaining a tempo if Black takes on e3 as he has played Bc5-a7-e3. Our plan is simple- exchange the bishops and then go for d4, Bf1.} 
10. Bxe3
11. Rxe3
11. Ne7
12. d4 {The first part of our plan is complete - we have secured control over the center. Now we have to maintain the control and finish our development.} 
12. c6
13. Bf1 {The bishop is well placed here, both in defence and offence. Bishops are long range pieces and they do not need to always be in the most active squares.} 
13. Ng6
14. c4 {We make use of the fact that the knight is still on b1 and can go directly to c3. This becomes strong when the knight has already gone to g6 as otherwise he can play c5 and bring the knight back to c6 and d4. You can check out more details here.} 
