7. Re1
7. a5 {One of the two major approaches to the position. Black prevents us from gaining space on the queenside. Now the Bxe6 fxe6 structures are not so appealing to us- Black will usually equalise comfortably. This is actually my main repertoire with the Black pieces. Anish, as per his overall approach, goes for quick d4-lines which are again, probably not more than a one-game try. I do not want to go for the absolute main lines, but at the same time, I want to recommend something which is critical and can be played over a long period of time.} 
8. h3 {I believe the inclusion of h3 and h6 is in White's favour in most lines in the Italian and this is no exception. Black's idea in this line is to go for Be6 and after Bb5 go for Qb8-a7. But he cannot do that unless White goes for Nbd2 (since otherwise White will be able to get d4 after Qb8).} 
8. h6 {Black also does the same. Now the main line is to go Nbd2 and allow Black to play Qb8-a7. I have analysed a couple of options there which are interesting at least for one game. I will give them as alternatives but without too much analysis. I would recommend you to first learn and understand our main line and then you can maybe include a few other options.} 
9. Bb5 {We anticipate the move Be6 and we get ready to play move d4. We make use of the drawbacks of the move a5. On the flip side, we are wasting a tempo. This has been played much less than Nbd2 and I feel that it is a big positive for us. Even though I was playing this variation with Black against many 2600+ players, I never prepared this move seriously until I started playing it with White.} 
9. Bd7 {The most human response- Black develops the bishop and covers the c6-knight. This is what I faced in my game against IM Srbis,J in Serbia Open 2022. However, it still does not solve the issue that d4 is always hanging in the air. Bd7 may be superfluous as it does not have a clear purpose.} 
10. Nbd2
10. a4 {This happened in my recent game against the strong Russian GM Alekseenko Kirill via a slightly different move order. I was not well aware of this particular setup and he was able to equalise easily.} 
11. Nf1
11. Ne7
12. Bxd7
12. Nxd7 {This is Black's point- he wants to go f5 next. This is very similar to Nakamura's idea in the Bb6 chapter.} 
13. d4
13. Bb6
14. Qc2 {Preparing to go Ng3, stopping move f5. You can check out more details here.} 
