8. Re1 {Just keep in mind not to play the move h3 before Black has castled. I am maybe repeating this excessively but better safe than sorry! Re1 is the most flexible move in almost all these positions. It helps prepare d4 as well as the plan with Nd2-f1-g3. Moreover in some lines, we can go for direct Be3 without playing Nbd2.} 
8. O-O
9. h3 {Now, there are two different ways to reach the Be6 fxe6 structures- either directly or with the inclusion of h6 and Nbd2. The more popular way is with the inclusion of h6 but the drawback is that h6 may become a weakness for Black and it does not have a real purpose. On the other hand, direct Be6 allows us to immediately exchange the dark-squared bishops with Be3, before even going for Nbd2.} 
9. Be6 {I actually think that this is the better version but only because of one concrete idea which has not been played much at all.} 
10. Bxe6
10. fxe6
11. Be3 {This might be a surprise for some of the people who have studied this course deeply so far. I have emphasized that we almost always follow up Bxe6 with b4, not giving Black the option to play a5. But chess cannot be explained by rigid rules. Here, Black is not able to go a5 and equalize as we go for a quick d4. In general, in the fxe6 structures, the exchange of a pair of minor pieces, especially the dark-squared bishops are in our favour. It helps stop Black's initiative on the kingside and also helps us go for d4.} 
11. Bxe3
12. Rxe3
12. a5 {Black tries to prove that we made an error in not going for b4 immediately.} 
13. d4 {We are too quick in the center.} 
13. Nd7
14. Na3 {We get the knight to the b5-square. This is usually not effective as Black can go for Ne7 and c6 but the knight on d7 makes that difficult. You can check out more details here.} 
