5. Nc3 {We are moving on to a more aggressive and dynamic version of the Italian that has not been deeply explored yet. We are developing our pieces faster than in the previous variations. The positions are quite symmetrical, and this increases the value of tempo for both sides. There are three major ideas here for us: go for Be3 and open the 'f' file for our rook, to go for a quick Bg5, and to meet the move d6 with Na4 winning the bishop pair.} 
5. d6 {The most played move in the database. For a long time, I felt this was just inaccurate, but it has been played by several top players, and things are not as simple.} 
6. Na4
6. Bb6
7. a3
7. O-O
8. O-O
8. h6
9. h3 {I am always a fan of this inclusion as we have no reason to be hesitant about the Bg4 ideas. Also, it gives us a square for our knight or king on h2.} 
9. Be6 {The most common idea for Black but it leads to structures that we are familiar with in the c3, d3-lines. It may be an even better version compared to that as we can win Black's dark-squared bishop.} 
10. Bxe6
10. fxe6
11. b4 {Again pretty similar to the Bc5 main lines. We go for b4 there too gaining space on the queenside.} 
11. Qe8
12. c3 {We cover the d4-square and also prepare to go for d4 or a4 in the future. Another upcoming plan is to go Ra2 covering the 2nd rank.} 
12. Nh5
13. Ra2 {Another idea borrowed from the Be6, fxe6-lines which we have seen in the c3, d3 chapters. We defend the f2-pawn and also have ideas of utilizing the rook along the second rank.} 
13. Qg6
14. Kh2
