5. a6
6. Bg5 {This is the main line in the position. We want to try and exploit the move a6, which is a non-developing move in the corner of the board. Our idea is to go Nd5 next. Initially, I was hesitant to just go for the most played moves. But then I had a game against Aryan Tari (2650 GM and a well-known opening theoretician) in the El Llobregat Open 2022 in this particular line. He was not familiar with the details, and I ended up getting more than an hour advantage on the clock with a better position. We will see that game, but it shows that the Nc3-line is still vastly unexplored, and we can catch most of our opponents off guard.} 
6. h6
7. Bxf6
7. Qxf6
8. Nd5 {This is the point of Bg5. We will try to keep our knight on d5 for as long as possible and go for the d4 break.} 
8. Qd8
9. c3 {Black has to decide how he wants to react to the move d4.} 
9. d6 {The most natural move strengthening the center.} 
10. d4
10. Ba7 {This is the move I would expect to happen in most of the games. Black maintains the tension in the center. Surprisingly Black has to play very accurately for the next 10 moves.} 
11. dxe5 {Already Black has to make a very important decision. In my game against Aryan Tari, he spent more than half an hour on this decision.} 
11. dxe5 {This is what I would expect in most games unless your opponent is a really strong player. It looks very natural to recapture with the pawn. However the problem for Black is our knight on d5 which is a monster now.} 
12. Qe2
12. Be6 {Natural but it does not address the problem of the 'd' file.} 
13. O-O-O {We castle and also bring the rook to the key 'd' file.} 
13. O-O
14. a3
14. Re8
15. g4 {Time to break open the kingside! White is just winning here.} 
