[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. g6 {This is a pretty decent way to play against the Ruy Lopez but here the bishop on c4 is slightly better placed. We should act immediately before Black can stop our d4 with Bg7.} 
4. d4 {We will look to punish most of these slow approaches by directly gaining control of the center. Another approach is to play more slowly with c3, d4, but it allows Black to consolidate and get a complex game which is exactly what he is aiming for!} 
4. exd4
5. Nxd4
5. Bg7
6. Nxc6 {One of my coaches always told me that every exchange that happens on the board should be evaluated carefully. We had several terms for these exchanges, based on the classic - My System by Nimzowitsch. This exchange would come under - 'Exchange to not lose a tempo' and 'Exchange with a preferable change in pawn structure'. When you have to clearly define the reason for a particular exchange, you tend to not make unnecessary exchanges!} 
6. bxc6
7. O-O {White has more control over the center, more space, and a superior pawn structure. When we have more space, the general rule is to not exchange too many minor pieces. However, it is not a very rigid rule and sometimes we do exchange a pair of pieces if we can gain something out of it. At the end of the day, it always depends on the position.} 
7. Ne7
8. Nc3 {Developing another piece while also discouraging any d5-breaks.} 
8. O-O
9. Be3 {We want to exchange Black's most active piece with Be3-d4. The dark squares will be a long-term weakness for Black.} 
9. d5
10. exd5
10. Bxc3
11. bxc3 {We should be really happy with this exchange. The dark squares are now a permanent weakness in Black's position. Along with the bishop pair, this gives us a good advantage!} 
11. cxd5
12. Be2 {We can continue with Qd2 followed by moves like Bg5/h6/d4 and play on the dark squares.} 
