4. Be7 {This is quite common across all levels. Usually, people go for this to avoid all the theory in the Bc5-lines and just get a solid playable position. It is important to note that the general guidelines here are a bit different from the main lines. We will go for a4 early and the main reason is that the structures with Bxe6, fxe6 are a better version for us as the Bishop on e7 is less active. In the main lines with Bc5 we go a4 only after Black goes for the move a6. Also, Nc3 setups are much more potent here, especially when Black tries to start play on the kingside with the move f5.} 
5. O-O
5. O-O
6. Re1 {White needs to stop the move d5.So far our plan is exactly the same as in the main lines. Re1 is a useful move in almost every version of the Italian. It creates a square on f1 for the knight and discourages the central break-d5.} 
6. d6
7. a4 {We create a luft for the bishop on a2. Black has many different options here. Our general guidelines are:  1) Stay flexible regarding the b1-knight until Black has shown his hand. Nc3-d5 is very effective if Black wants to play on the kingside. Also, unlike the main lines we do not want to go for c3 very early as we want the option to go for Nc3-d5. Black has to commit to some plan in the next couple of moves and we will react accordingly. We have a useful waiting move in h3 if needed.  2) We usually try to go for a5 and fix the pawn structure in our favour on the queenside. Different people go for different approaches- some like to play a5 and others want to keep options open. I feel going for a5 at the right moment makes a lot of sense- to gain space and also prepare the move Qb3.} 
7. Bg4 {This makes more sense when White has already played Nc3 but here we can always go for Nbd2 followed by Nf1-g3. It is quite common according to online databases but it is only Black's bishop which gets kicked around to a worse square.} 
8. h3
8. Bh5
9. c3 {We stop Nd4 ideas and next we go Nd2-f1-g3.} 
9. d5 {The only way to try to justify Bg4. After anything else we will just continue with Nbd2-f1-g3.} 
10. exd5
10. Nxd5
11. a5 {This serves two functions here. 1) It gains space on the queenside and potentially creates a weakness on b7. 2) It prepares the move Qb3 without allowing Na5.} 
11. a6
12. Nbd2 {Our plan is to go Ne4-g3.} 
12. b5 {This is the typical idea to counter the move a5 in these lines. Black makes use of the fact that the d3-pawn is not well protected.} 
13. axb6
13. Nxb6
14. g4
14. Bg6
15. Rxa6 {Black has to now prove his compensation.} 
15. Nxc4
16. Rxa8
16. Qxa8
17. Nxc4
17. f6 {We are always happy to see this as it weakens his kingside in the long term.} 
18. Nh4
18. Bf7
19. Qf3 {Engines feel Black has some compensation for the pawn but it is very difficult to understand over the board. We will continue with Nf5 or g5. Another strong idea is to bring the other knight to e4 via d2.} 
