9. Qe8 {Black is aiming to go Nh5-f4 and maybe bring the queen to g6. But he does allow us to demonstrate our main idea.} 
10. b4
10. a6
11. Qb3 {This is very common once Black goes for Qe8. He has to either waste another tempo defending the pawn or expose his center with the move d5.} 
11. d5
12. Bg5 {We indirectly attack the center by putting pressure on the key defender. Doubled pawns are pretty decent statically but if you start playing dynamically with them, they get exposed. With the pawn on d6, it was difficult for us to exploit them but now it is a different story.} 
12. Qf7
13. Nbd2
13. h6
14. Bxf6
14. Bxf6
15. h3 {We can prepare move c4 especially when the c6-knight is kicked out. The Black bishop is pretty miserable.} 
