7. Na5 {This is the main line in the Be7 system but it has gone out of fashion in recent years at the top level. The play here is very similar to Ruy Lopez lines and we have a slightly better version here as the bishop has not wasted as many tempi.} 
8. Ba2 {We plan to play c3 followed by Na3, Nc2/c4, and then go for Bd2, b4. We can interchange the move orders depending on Black's plan. In some cases, Bg5 becomes very attractive to get to the d5-square.} 
8. c5 {Black gets more control over the d4-square but at the same time weakens the d5-square massively. Ideally, it would be great if we could exchange all the minor pieces except for our knight and Black's dark-squared bishop. But of course, it is not that simple. We can use the c5-pawn as a hook to start play on the queenside with b2-b4 and at the same time bring the knight to e3, eyeing the d5-square.} 
9. c3 {We have two broad plans- to get b4 with Bd2 and to get the knight to e3. Whenever Black plays the move Be6, we take, not allowing Black to take on a2 or play Qd7-e6.} 
9. Nc6 {Black tries to delay our plan of b2-b4.} 
10. Na3 {The knight is much more flexible here as it can go to both c4, c2 and also it keeps the option of going Bd2/g5 alive.} 
10. Be6 {This is quite critical here. Black immediately forces us to take on e6 and he will aim to go d5 quickly. We have to be precise. I have analysed this extremely deeply and have come up with many new ideas. I do not think it is necessary to study all of that but I feel it would definitely help improve your general chess understanding.} 
11. Bxe6
11. fxe6
12. Bd2 {Preparing both b4 and an eventual Rc1. Once we have taken on e6, the plan of bringing the knight to e3 is less effective.} 
12. Qe8
13. b4 {We want to take on c5 next. In the future we want to push b5 and play d4.} 
13. cxb4
14. cxb4
14. Qg6 {Black's idea is to go for Ng4 followed by initiative along the 'f' file.} 
15. Qe2 {Keeping an eye on the f2-pawn and also the center.} 
15. Nh5
16. b5
16. Nd4 {Black has to go forward. He cannot allow us to play d4.} 
17. Nxd4
17. exd4
18. Nc4 {We are threatening to go for e5 next.} 
18. e5
19. Rf1 {Positionally we are doing much better with our knight on c4. If given time, we will completely take over.} 
19. Bg5 {Black is fighting for the f4-square.} 
20. Bxg5
20. Qxg5
21. Nxd6 {We are not afraid of any ghosts.} 
21. Nf4
22. Qa2+
22. Kh8
23. g3
23. Qg6
24. Qa3
24. Nxd3
25. f3 {The position is still complex but Black's initiative has come to an end and his knight will get pushed back.} 
