11. Bxe6
11. fxe6
12. Bd2 {Preparing both b4 and an eventual Rc1. Once we have taken on e6, the plan of bringing the knight to e3 is less effective.} 
12. a6
13. h3 {This is a novelty in over-the-board chess. But it has been played a number of times in correspondance chess. We have seen (and will see) this move in a number of occasions in the Italian. It helps protect our kingside and is also a kind of waiting move.} 
13. Rb8 {This has been played in a few games. A general point to remember- whenever Black goes for Rb8 we immediately go for Nc4 and after b5 we take and go Ne3. We get the 'a' file for free.} 
14. Nc4
14. b5
15. axb5
15. axb5
16. Ne3 {A typical plan in these positions is to go Ng4 next and also create some play on the kingside. We can basically play on any side of the board :)} 
