[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Italian 3...Nf6 - Solid Be7"]
[Black "Italian 3...Nf6 4...Be7 - Solid Be7 7...Na5  #9"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Be7 {This is quite common across all levels. Usually, people go for this to avoid all the theory in the Bc5-lines and just get a solid playable position. It is important to note that the general guidelines here are a bit different from the main lines. We will go for a4 early and the main reason is that the structures with Bxe6, fxe6 are a better version for us as the Bishop on e7 is less active. In the main lines with Bc5 we go a4 only after Black goes for the move a6. Also, Nc3 setups are much more potent here, especially when Black tries to start play on the kingside with the move f5.} 
5. O-O
5. O-O
6. Re1 {White needs to stop the move d5.So far our plan is exactly the same as in the main lines. Re1 is a useful move in almost every version of the Italian. It creates a square on f1 for the knight and discourages the central break-d5.} 
6. d6
7. a4 {We create a luft for the bishop on a2. Black has many different options here. Our general guidelines are:  1) Stay flexible regarding the b1-knight until Black has shown his hand. Nc3-d5 is very effective if Black wants to play on the kingside. Also, unlike the main lines we do not want to go for c3 very early as we want the option to go for Nc3-d5. Black has to commit to some plan in the next couple of moves and we will react accordingly. We have a useful waiting move in h3 if needed.  2) We usually try to go for a5 and fix the pawn structure in our favour on the queenside. Different people go for different approaches- some like to play a5 and others want to keep options open. I feel going for a5 at the right moment makes a lot of sense- to gain space and also prepare the move Qb3.} 
7. Na5 {This is the main line in the Be7 system but it has gone out of fashion in recent years at the top level. The play here is very similar to Ruy Lopez lines and we have a slightly better version here as the bishop has not wasted as many tempi.} 
8. Ba2 {We plan to play c3 followed by Na3, Nc2/c4, and then go for Bd2, b4. We can interchange the move orders depending on Black's plan. In some cases, Bg5 becomes very attractive to get to the d5-square.} 
8. c5 {Black gets more control over the d4-square but at the same time weakens the d5-square massively. Ideally, it would be great if we could exchange all the minor pieces except for our knight and Black's dark-squared bishop. But of course, it is not that simple. We can use the c5-pawn as a hook to start play on the queenside with b2-b4 and at the same time bring the knight to e3, eyeing the d5-square.} 
9. c3 {We have two broad plans- to get b4 with Bd2 and to get the knight to e3. Whenever Black plays the move Be6, we take, not allowing Black to take on a2 or play Qd7-e6.} 
9. Nc6 {Black tries to delay our plan of b2-b4.} 
10. Na3 {The knight is much more flexible here as it can go to both c4, c2 and also it keeps the option of going Bd2/g5 alive.} 
10. h6 {The most played move in the position. Black is not in a hurry to commit to a particular plan and just keeps improving his position slowly. I feel it is a bit slow and more of a safe option from Black.} 
11. Bd2 {We prepare the move b4.} 
11. Re8 {This plan is too slow. We can get to the d5-square in time.} 
12. Nc2
12. Bf8
13. Ne3
13. Be6
14. Bxe6
14. Rxe6 {Given time, Black will want to play d5 but chess is often a game of one tempo!} 
15. c4 {We can go for Nd5 next with a nice edge.} 
