4. h6 {This is a fairly modern trend gaining popularity from 2019 onwards. Black wants to develop his bishop on g7 with either g6/g5. In both cases, h6 is essential to stop Ng5 or prepare g5. This was recommended by Sethuraman in his LTR course and has been played by many top players (mostly the g5 system). It may be a good weapon to get a fighting game for Black players but we should be welcoming it. Black is not going to get a huge attack on the kingside and we have a good chance to punish him in the center.} 
5. O-O {We are not afraid of Black's attack in the slightest. It is more of a long-term strategy for Black and he usually castles kingside even after g5. Black claims that g4 is always hanging in the air and it is not that easy for us to play d4.} 
5. d6 {Black has to do this before going for g5/g6 as otherwise we will go for the direct d4 break in the center.} 
6. c3 {We are following our usual developing plan, similar to the main lines after Bc5. Previously Black always used to go for g6, but it was quickly discovered that life is not easy for Black there. The resurgence of this variation is primarily based on the g5 system.} 
6. g5 {The modern computer era discovery. Black is not so much trying to attack on the kingside as is gaining space and preventing White from gaining control over the center easily.} 
7. Nbd2 {Why do we do this instead of the usual a4?   1) The knight belongs on e3 exploiting the weakness on f5 and also keeping an eye on the d5-square. The usual route- Nd2-f1-e3 is not possible with the rook on f1 and we are preparing the alternate route via c4   2) One of Black's main ideas is to go for d5 gaining space in the center. Now d5 can be met with the strong d4 blowing open the center in our favour.   3) It helps us go d3-d4 without worrying about exd4 cxd4 d5/Ne4 type of ideas.} 
7. Bg7
8. Bb3 {One thing we need to remember here is to NOT play Re1 for two reasons-   1) We may need the square for the knight after g5-g4   2) The rook may get active in the future along the 'f' line after a potential f2-f3/f4.   Another thing which I keep stressing on throughout the course- NEVER play h3 in these positions after O-O unless Black has also castled.} 
8. g4 {As usual, this is just asking for it as we will soon break with f3/f4.} 
9. Ne1
9. h5 {This is too slow with the king in the center.} 
10. f4
10. exf4
11. Rxf4
11. d5 {This happened in a classical game between 2 2700+ players in the 2022 Grand Prix. But White is already winning here: 1-0 (33) Dominguez Perez, L (2752)-Shirov, A (2704) Berlin 2022} 
12. exd5
12. Nxd5
13. Rf2 {There is no response to the simple plan of Ne4, Bg5 or even just d4. Black's king is going to come under a ton of pressure.} 
