[Black "Italian 4...Bc5 - Dubious sidelines 5...h6"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Bc5 {This is the starting position of the main lines in the Italian with the bishop on c5. It can arise from both 3...Nf6 and 3...Bc5 move orders. They are quite different to the lines which we have seen so far, but they do have some key similarities.  One of the major structures here to know about is the lines with Be6 which we will analyse very deeply. The general rule is that those structures are great for us if we manage to get in a4 and b4 in the queenside. If Black manages to get the move a5 it is usually fine for him. So we tend to rush with b4.   In this chapter we will look at some of the rare and dubious sidelines for Black which are especially popular in online games. Some of these moves are more popular than even the absolute main lines in the online database and at the club level. So we will take them seriously and try to just refute them. Also I will give an overview of some of the general rules and guidelines in this entire system.} 
5. c3
5. h6 {Will also mostly transpose to one of our main lines.} 
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. b4
7. Bb6
8. a4
8. a6 {Is forced and now we get the usual positions with the bishop being on b6 which will come under attack with Nd2-c4 or a5.} 
9. Nbd2
9. d6
10. h3 {We will go Re1 next. At best, Black can go for the Be6 positions which are very comfortable for White.} 
