[White "5) Italian 4...Bc5 5.c3 - Dubious sidelines"]
[Black "Italian 4...Bc5 - Dubious sidelines 5...d5"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Bc5 {This is the starting position of the main lines in the Italian with the bishop on c5. It can arise from both 3...Nf6 and 3...Bc5 move orders. They are quite different to the lines which we have seen so far, but they do have some key similarities.  One of the major structures here to know about is the lines with Be6 which we will analyse very deeply. The general rule is that those structures are great for us if we manage to get in a4 and b4 in the queenside. If Black manages to get the move a5 it is usually fine for him. So we tend to rush with b4.   In this chapter we will look at some of the rare and dubious sidelines for Black which are especially popular in online games. Some of these moves are more popular than even the absolute main lines in the online database and at the club level. So we will take them seriously and try to just refute them. Also I will give an overview of some of the general rules and guidelines in this entire system.} 
5. c3 {There are no serious independent options here for Black. The slight drawback is that we can no longer go for Nc3, but that does not affect us in any way. If we want to go for those lines we start with 5.Nc3.} 
5. d5 {Too early. All of Black's pieces are shaky in the center with the king still in the middle of the board.} 
6. exd5
6. Nxd5
7. Qb3 {We are already winning material on move 7.} 
7. Nf6
8. Bxf7+
8. Kf8 {The only thing going in Black's favour is that we are behind in development.} 
9. O-O {Of course, we do not care about the d3-pawn. We will get a lot of tempi when Black takes the pawn. Many players get tempted by material in these positions and get their pieces stuck in awkward squares.} 
9. Qxd3 {The best move by far. Otherwise, we just consolidate with our extra pawn.} 
10. Bc4
10. Qd6
11. Rd1
11. Qe7
12. Nbd2 {We have almost completed our development. Black on the other hand, has hardly done anything over the last 4 moves, other than opening up the center by grabbing our pawn. e4 will be met strongly with Nd4 and it is only a matter of time before the black king comes under fire.} 
