[Black "Italian 4...Bc5 - Dubious sidelines 5...d6  #3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Bc5 {This is the starting position of the main lines in the Italian with the bishop on c5. It can arise from both 3...Nf6 and 3...Bc5 move orders. They are quite different to the lines which we have seen so far, but they do have some key similarities.  One of the major structures here to know about is the lines with Be6 which we will analyse very deeply. The general rule is that those structures are great for us if we manage to get in a4 and b4 in the queenside. If Black manages to get the move a5 it is usually fine for him. So we tend to rush with b4.   In this chapter we will look at some of the rare and dubious sidelines for Black which are especially popular in online games. Some of these moves are more popular than even the absolute main lines in the online database and at the club level. So we will take them seriously and try to just refute them. Also I will give an overview of some of the general rules and guidelines in this entire system.} 
5. c3
5. d6 {This is the most common and logical move. I have mentioned before that when we have a variety of possible move orders, it makes a lot of sense to go for the most necessary move first. In all of the lines, Black usually goes for d6.} 
6. O-O
6. a6 {This is the main, traditional setup for Black in the Italian and it can happen via different move orders. Here Black delays O-O for a few reasons-   1) Bg5 lines are less effective for us but we do not go for them anyway.   2) Black is hoping for White to commit the move h3 after which he can start an immediate attack with h6-g5.} 
7. a4 {The general rule for our Italian is to meet the move a6 with a4. We do not go for the move a4 without a6 in most cases. This is because the positions after a4, a5 are usually totally fine for Black. Now we want to potentially play b4 in the future and create play on the queenside.} 
7. Ba7
8. Re1 {Another general rule- Never go for h3 before Black has castled on the kingside. This is because h3 creates a hook for Black to play g5-g4. If you check with a computer, it will say that h3 is also fine here planning to meet h6 with Be3. But there is no real benefit of going for h3 early. And if there was Re1 and h6 already included, g5 would be pretty bad for us.} 
8. O-O
9. h3 {Now is the right time to go h3. We stop any kind of Ng4 or Bg4 ideas in the future and we also safeguard our kingside.} 
9. h6
10. Nbd2
10. Qe7 {Black prepares Be6 with his queen. The drawback is that now he cannot go for the d5 break easily. The queen is not that comfortable along the 'e' file.} 
11. Bb3 {Next we want to go Nf1-g3 and meet Be6 with Bc2.} 
11. Be6
12. Nc4 {We stop d5 ideas and we will slowly prepare the move Be3.} 
12. Rad8
13. a5 {We fix the pawn structure on the queenside and stop a potential b5. Next, we will continue with Be3.} 
13. Rfe8
14. Be3
14. Bxe3
15. Nxe3
15. Bxb3
16. Qxb3 {We have multiple ideas here. We can go for our usual break with d4, We could also go for Qa4 and c4, b4 on the queenside.} 
