[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Bc5
5. c3
5. O-O {Black is flexible regarding his d pawn, keeping options of both d6 and d5 open. One of the drawbacks is that Bg5 is more dangerous now compared to before Black castled, but it still leads to very messy positions with chances for both sides.   Black is threatening to go d5 and it is not very easy to stop. Playing Re1 allows Ng4 and after every other natural move, d5 is possible. We need to study this line carefully as it is very concrete and we cannot rely solely on concepts and ideas. Black players usually go for this to try and equalize directly.} 
6. O-O {We continue with our normal plan allowing d5. One of the things I like about this line for White is that Black has to be very well prepared and we have several ways to pose problems. In many lines, Black has to give up some material and he needs to know exactly how to prove his compensation.} 
6. d5
7. exd5
7. Nxd5 {This is a critical position in this system and we have a number of different options. We can go after the central pawn, play on the queenside or prevent the move Bg4. All of the moves have their own merits and demerits.} 
8. Re1 {This is the most natural and common move putting more pressure on the center. We should play quite energetically here as Black will be very comfortable once he bolsters his center.} 
8. Re8 {A huge mistake that I see often in blitz/bullet when Black does not know the theory well. The queen on d8 gets overloaded after} 
9. d4
9. Be7
10. Nxe5
10. Nxe5
11. dxe5 {We have a clean extra pawn.} 
