11. b4 {This is an old line that many people would be unfamiliar with. Bb3 and Bb5 are much more popular. We gain space on the queenside with tempo and also create a potential threat of b4-b5. My approach to opening preparation has always been to choose theoretically sound main lines, but then find my own way to pose problems. Rather than go deep into the main lines, it makes a lot of sense to force our opponent to think on his own, as early as possible.} 
11. Be7 {Keeping an eye on the d3 pawn. Already this is not an obvious decision if Black is not well prepared. Many players tend to underestimate slightly older lines and instead focus most of their time on the latest trends. We can utilize this to catch our opponents off guard.} 
12. Qe2 {This is a very rare idea in OTB chess. I played one of the two games here and it is actually quite unpleasant to meet with Black. It is very likely that Black is out of his prep and we are just starting. We are threatening to go Bb3 and also potentially g4 and Nf3-e5.} 
12. Nxc4 {Black has to get rid of the bishop when he can. Now if he is just able to consolidate, he might even take over. We need to act extremely dynamically in the center.} 
13. Nxc4 {We have ideas of b5 or g4 followed by winning the e5 pawn. Black has to make some concession. He does have the bishop pair though and so he can afford to even give up material at some point and get good compensation.} 
13. f6 {This is definitely what I would expect from my opponent. The problem for Black is that now his king is getting exposed.  13... Re8 14. b5 Nb8 15. g4 Bg6 16. Ncxe5⩲} 
14. b5
14. Nb8
15. d4 {We strike before Black can bring his knight back into the game. We will not hesitate to play g4 at the right moment. Black has to make a tough decision here. I have shown this position to a few of my GM friends and no one was able to equalize cleanly.} 
15. Nd7 {A few people felt that this should be holdable for Black but they just completely underestimated the danger.} 
16. dxe5
16. fxe5 {The line is pretty forcing.} 
17. Ncxe5
17. Nxe5
18. Qxe5
18. Bxf3
19. Qxe7 {And usually people assumed that this would be a draw. But it is very far from the truth. The pawn on b5 is a big blessing for us and it creates a lot of targets along the 7th rank. Engines give more than a +1 advantage for White and practically it is extremely difficult for Black to survive.} 
19. Bd5
20. Bg5
20. Qxe7
21. Rxe7 {Opposite colour bishops endgames with rooks on the board is usually not easy to defend. We should just make sure that we have at least one pair of rooks on the board.} 
