[Black "Italian 4...Bc5 - Trendy Bb6 8...h6  #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Bc5
5. c3
5. d6 {This is the most common approach, not opting for forcing, direct lines. Black has several different setups here. Our plan is usually to either gain space on the queenside or break with d3-d4 in the centre at the right moment. Broadly Black has 2 major approaches- try to create play on the kingside or counter White's play on the queenside and centre.} 
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. Re1 {The rook on e1 is useful in all the lines - preparing d4 or Nd2-f1-g3 or even Be3. I prefer not to commit any pawn moves so early. As we know, when we have a choice between a few decent options we go for the most necessary one first.} 
7. Bb6 {This is a modern trend- Black prepares to go Ne7-g6 followed by d5 and will meet a4 with c6. Initially Black was always going for a7-a6, but then they realized that it was not that easy after a4, b4 on the queenside. So here Black will try to meet our play on the queenside with the thematic d5.} 
8. h3 {In these lines I prefer to first play all our useful moves before committing to a particular plan. We want Black to show his hand first and we will base our plan around that. For example, if Black goes for a quick Ne7-g6 we can then go d4 and Bf1 in one go. Black can also try to be clever and first play all his useful moves- it is a cat-and-mouse game.} 
8. h6
9. Nbd2 {This is always necessary. The only drawback is that we can no longer go for d4 directly. But Black is anyway going to go for Ne7 in most cases.} 
9. a5 {This is a speciality of Hikaru Nakamura. He has played around 20 games in various online events. It usually arises from a different move order.} 
10. Bb5 {This is my main recommendation in the a5-variations and it actually transposes to one of the lines there. We anticipate Be6 and also vacate the square for the knight potentially. Why do we meet Be6 with Bb5? As we will see, the Bxe6 fxe6 structures work very well for us only if we manage to get in the move b4. Black has already played a5 here and is usually fine in those positions.} 
10. Ne7 {Is not the 'Hikaru' plan.} 
11. d4 {We get our break in the center and next we will aim to follow up with Nf1-g3, usually after playing Bd3-c2. We should always check if Black can play d5 in these positions, with or without capturing on d4.} 
11. c6
12. Bd3
12. Ng6
13. Nf1
13. Re8
14. Ng3 {This is the optimum setup for our pieces. Ideally, we will continue with Be3, Qd2 and maybe Rad1 bringing all our pieces into the game. Black always has to watch out for Bxh6 ideas and the knight jumping to f5.} 
14. Be6
15. a4 {We stop Black from going a5-a4 in the future.} 
15. Bc7
16. Bd2 {We do not oblige. We keep an eye on the e5-pawn, stopping d5 ideas. We will continue with Qc2 and Rad1.} 
