7. Re1
7. a5 {One of the two major approaches to the position. Black prevents us from gaining space on the queenside. Now the Bxe6 fxe6 structures are not so appealing to us- Black will usually equalize comfortably. This is my main repertoire with the black pieces. Anish, as per his overall approach, goes for quick d4-lines which are again, probably not more than a one-game try. I do not want to go for the absolute main lines, but at the same time, I want to recommend something that is critical and can be played over a long period.} 
8. h3 {I believe the inclusion of h3 and h6 is in White's favour in most lines in the Italian and this is no exception. Black's idea in this line is to go for Be6 and after Bb5 go for Qb8-a7. But Black cannot do that unless White goes for Nbd2 (since otherwise White will be able to get d4 after Qb8).} 
8. h6 {Black also does the same. Now the main line is to go Nbd2 and allow Black to play Qb8-a7. I have analysed a couple of options there which are interesting at least for one game. I will give them as alternatives but without too much analysis. I would recommend you to first learn and understand our main line and then you can maybe include a few other options.} 
9. Bb5 {We anticipate the move Be6 and we get ready to play move d4. We make use of the drawbacks of the move a5. On the flip side, we are wasting a tempo. This has been played much less than Nbd2 and I feel that it is a big positive for us. Even though I was playing this variation with Black against many 2600+ players, I never prepared this move seriously until I started playing it with White.} 
9. Ba7 {Black prophylactically moves the bishop away from the vulnerable c5-square.} 
10. Nbd2
10. Ne7 {This is usually our indication to go d3-d4. We can follow up with either Bd3-c2 or Bf1 as we saw in the previous chapter.} 
11. d4
11. Ng6
12. Bd3 {We get our bishop to c2 supporting the e4-pawn and also keeping the square on f1 open for the knight.} 
12. Nh5 {As usual this is always annoying whenever we go to d3. But once again there are no games here which is a good thing for us. Also, engines claim this is fine for Black but practically Black has to play a lot of only moves while we have a few options to pose critical problems.} 
13. Nf1
13. Qf6 {Black is looking to start his play on the kingside very quickly.} 
14. Bc2
14. Nhf4
15. Ng3
15. Re8
16. Nf5 {Black cannot touch our knight on f5 and we will go for Be3 next. Black has only one good way to fight back.} 
16. c5 {This is certainly not a standard move in the Italian but it does happen in the Ruy Lopez, for instance in the Breyer/Chigorin variation. Black forces us to close the center and luckily Black is in time to open the diagonal for his bishop with c5-c4.} 
17. d5
17. c4 {Only move. If only White was in time to play c3-c4 he would be winning. If White could just get a4 and Be3 he would be much better here. But it is all a game of tempo.} 
18. Be3 {We get rid of the dangerous bishop on a7.} 
18. b5
19. b3 {We want to create some weakness on the queenside too.} 
19. cxb3
20. axb3
20. Bxf5
21. exf5
21. Ne7
22. Nd2 {The position is pretty complicated. You guys can check this out further. Black must be very accurate in this entire line.} 
