[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Italian 4...Bc5 5.c3 - Cunning a6-a5"]
[Black "Italian 4...Bc5 - Cunning a6-a5 10...Ne7"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Bc5
5. c3
5. d6
6. O-O
6. a6 {We have come to the traditional main line for Black in the Italian. Everyone used to go for this and equalize comfortably. Black's plan was just O-O followed by Be6. People later realized that if White can get b4, a4 in those positions it was pretty unpleasant for Black. Black cannot create any kind of dangerous attack in the kingside.} 
7. a4 {As a rule, we always meet a6 with a4. Now we are happy to go into Be6, fe6 structures as will quickly get in the move b4 gaining a lot of space on the queenside. Once we have gone b4 and a4, we do not rush to begin our play on the queenside. Remember, the threat is better than the execution! Black always has to be worried about a potential b4-b5 and in the meantime, we will fully secure our kingside. Only after that do we either go for b4-b5 or the central break d4.} 
7. h6 {Another important rule- NEVER go h3 unless Black has castled. I will be repeating this throughout the course. I have won so many blitz games from the Black side when my opponent carelessly played h2-h3 creating a hook for me to go g5-g4.} 
8. Re1
8. O-O
9. h3 {I feel this is more flexible as we very rarely delay playing move h3. The main lines here are usually related to the move Be6 or Ne7-g6.} 
9. a5 {This was really intriguing for me when I started playing the Italian. Black claims that he is even willing to lose a whole tempo to get this pawn structure on the queenside. Black wants to go Be6 next and meet Bb5 with Na7 when we do not have the square on a4 for the bishop. Why do we need to play Bb5? Because the structure after Be6 fxe6 is usually fine for Black unless we can get a4 and b4 on the queenside.   This is a very serious attempt to equalize with Black and it is not that easy to pose problems. But on the other hand, it is much lesser known and not likely to happen in most of our games. I have never faced this much (even online) in the last 4 years.} 
10. Bb5 {This has been played very rarely (3 human games out of more than 100 games). We are already very familiar with this move from the previous chapter. We anticipate Black going for Be6 and go for Bb5 ourselves. In the previous chapter, we saw this exact position with the pawn still on a2. This does lead to some key differences.} 
10. Ne7
11. d4 {If Black retreats with his bishop we can go for our usual plan with Bd3, Nd2-f1-g3, or Nd2 and Bf1. a4 is useful for us in these positions.} 
11. exd4
12. cxd4
12. Bb4 {This would have been more effective if White had played Nbd2 already.} 
13. Bd2
13. Bxd2
14. Nbxd2 {We will continue with either Ra3 or Nf1-g3 next. Black does not have enough activity to compensate for giving up the center.} 
