8. Re1
8. h6 {I like to go for this move order against lower-rated people with Black sometimes, just hoping that they would go h3. I have even won against a few good GMs as Black in this move order when they went h3 here.} 
9. Nbd2
9. g5 {Black goes g5 anyway hoping to start some initiative on the kingside. But as we saw in the 3...Nf6 and 4...h6 chapter Black cannot create much of an attack on the kingside as long as White's pawn is on h2. This is well known to be a bit dubious for Black but we do need to study this carefully to exploit it.} 
10. b4 {We start our play on the queenside and the center. b4-b5 is quite annoying for Black in many positions. Since Black's king is still in the center we will not hesitate to go d4 and sacrifice our pawns to blast open the center} 
10. Nh7 {This became a trend for a short period of time. I faced this against Sethuraman in the Abu Dhabi Masters 2022 (the game is included in the model games section). I got a completely winning position very quickly even though I did not have much idea about the position. White's play is actually very simple and logical if we understand the general Italian ideas. Remember you can almost always go for d4 and usually Black cannot capture our pawn without getting his king into trouble.} 
11. Kh1
11. O-O
12. Rf1
12. Ne7
13. Bb3 {We will go d4 and Nc4 next. There is no hint of any kind of attack on the kingside.} 
13. Ng6
14. d4
14. Qf6
15. Nc4
15. Bg4
16. Ne3 {Please give us your light-squared bishop and then we will see who attacks whom.} 
16. Bxf3
17. Qxf3
17. Qxf3
18. gxf3 {We are ready to jump to f5 next. The exchange of queens does not slow down our initiative in any way.} 
18. Nh4
19. Ng2 {Change of plans- We exchange off his most active piece!} 
19. Nxg2
20. Kxg2
20. exd4
21. Bb2 {Our initiative does not end with these exchanges. We are threatening to go h4 next and start an attack on the kingside. The bishop on a7 looks good but it is stuck there, firing at thin air.} 
