[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Bc5
5. c3
5. d6
6. O-O
6. a6
7. a4
7. Ba7 {One key rule to remember in the a6 system- NEVER go h3 before Black has castled on the kingside. h3 creates a hook on the kingside for Black to break with g5-g4.} 
8. Re1
8. O-O
9. h3
9. Kh8 {This creative idea gained popularity back in 2019 and was played by many top players. But it was abandoned soon after. Black wants to go Ng8 and f5 next.} 
10. d4 {Of course, we meet every one of these unprincipled lines with our favourite central break. We will go Be3 next if given the chance.} 
10. h6 {This does not make a lot of sense as Black is combining different plans. It was played by Aronian once in the Olympiad in 2022.} 
11. Be3 {We will go for dxe5 next as the move Kh8 has created another weakness on f7.} 
11. exd4 {This is a typical reaction but the move Kh8 does not really fit in with this plan.} 
12. cxd4
12. d5
13. exd5
13. Nxd5
14. Bxd5 {We give up our bishop to gain two tempi and also we will look to start our play on the dark squares next as Black's dark-squared bishop is stuck on a7.} 
14. Qxd5
15. Nc3
15. Qd6
16. a5 {We will follow up with Qd2 and Bf4 next. Whenever Black touches his c6-knight we can jump to e5 with ours.} 
