2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Bc5
5. c3
5. d6
6. O-O
6. a6
7. a4
7. Ba7
8. Re1
8. O-O
9. h3
9. h6
10. Nbd2
10. Re8 {This is one of the huge main lines in the Italian with the plan of Be6 next. We will look at this in the final chapter. Here we will look at a sneaky sideline after Re8.} 
11. b4 {Whenever Black goes for Re8 it is time for us to go for b2-b4. If we go for b4 earlier, the Ne7-g6 plan works well for Black as the queenside becomes more of a weakness. Now, according to conventional wisdom, Black should not go Ne7 as the f7-pawn will come under attack. But in modern chess, nothing is as straightforward as it looks.} 
11. Ne7 {I faced this in a very recent and painful game against Durarbayli, V in the Sitges open 2022. It is the only game I have lost in classical chess in the Bc5-variation but it is not really about the opening part.} 
12. Qb3 {This is well known and Black is forced to defend the pawn with his rook once again.} 
12. Rf8
13. d4 {We have managed to get our break in the center without too much effort but Black argues that the queen is not well placed on b3.} 
13. Ng6 {This was a surprise for me. I felt it should be kind of dubious, during the game, and was looking at ways to punish it. I should have just continued with normal, natural moves.} 
14. a5 {We fix the pawn structure on the queenside. We want to continue with Nf1 or Bf1 next depending on Black's move.} 
14. c6
15. Bf1 {Black was ready to play d5 so we bring our bishop back to f1. The knight can now jump to c4 and try to exploit the b6-square.} 
15. Be6
16. Qc2
16. exd4
17. cxd4 {We have good control over the center. Black cannot really play d5 anytime soon.} 
17. Qd7
18. Ba3 {We will follow up with Rad1 next. We should slowly prepare to play Nc4 or go for the d5 break with Bb2 later on.} 
