12. Bb3 {This is pretty rare in this position, but fully in the spirit of our repertoire. We are ready to go d4 next while Black is not in time to go d5 before us. Our play is more or less similar in all these lines- play d4 and then bring the bishop to c2.} 
12. c6
13. d4
13. d5 {The critical way to combat our control in the center. It has been played only once though in over-the-board chess.} 
14. dxe5 {We want to preserve the extra pair of minor pieces on the board. The knight on f3 can jump to d4 when needed.} 
14. Nxe4
15. Be3 {We will be very happy if Black exchanges the bishops. We can then continue with N1d2 dislodging the knight on e4.} 
15. Bb8
16. Bd4 {We want to go c4 next. If we get to play c4 and take on d5, the d4-square would be a great outpost for our pieces.} 
16. c5
17. Be3
17. c4
18. Bc2 {If given a chance, we will be much better after Bd4. Positionally we are already doing great if we manage to hold on to the e5-pawn.} 
18. Nxe5 {Black has to shake things up.} 
19. Nxe5
19. Bxe5
20. f3 {We are looking to win back the pawn while maintaining some positional edge.} 
20. Nf6
21. Bxh6 {We win the h6-pawn in return for our e5-pawn. It has both its benefits and drawbacks. Black gets a better hold over the center but his king is now more exposed.} 
21. Re8
22. Bg5 {We want to go f4 next. Black has weakened the d4-square by going c5-c4. The d5-pawn is a weakness we will try to exploit. And the kingside will be a perennial problem for Black without the 'h' pawn.} 
