8. Re1
8. O-O
9. h3
9. Ne7 {Black wants to regroup his knight to g6 and will aim to play c6, d5 in the center. This has a lot of similarities to the Bb6 chapter which evolved from this system. I have played this in several games in the past with the Black pieces. The drawback of this system is that Black allows us to take control of the center easily. Our ideal setup would be to play d4, Bd3/ b3-c2, Nd2-f1-g3 and Be3. At the same time we need to always be ready to deal with the d5 break.} 
10. d4 {Given the chance, we go for the d4 break immediately. This is one of the reasons why many players go for h6 first. They play Ne7 only after Nbd2 when d4 is not as effective.} 
10. Ng6
11. Nbd2
11. Re8 {Black does not want to commit the move c6 which can create a weakness on the queenside. Also, he is aiming for the plan of Bd7-c6 provoking us to go for the move d5 which will open the diagonal for his other bishop. We continue in the same way as our main line.} 
12. Bd3 {The ideal square for the bishop is on c2 keeping an eye on the e4-pawn and at the same time ready for any potential operations on both flanks.} 
12. Bd7 {Black prepares to go b5 next. He can also play Bc6 putting pressure on our center. It does also connect the rooks to prepare the move d5 in the future.} 
13. a5 {We immediately stop his plan of b5 and also fix a weakness on b7. In these lines, we should always be asking ourselves what our opponent is aiming for. In some cases, we can make a useful move, which also stops his idea. This is the perfect prophylaxis. Even otherwise, stopping his idea often makes the opponent irritated and more prone to rash decisions.} 
13. h6
14. Bc2 {Our bishop has reached its ideal square on c2. Next, we will look to bring our knight to g3. This is not only to play on the kingside but also because the knight on g3 both solidifies our center and also allows us to go for Be3 and Qd2.} 
14. Bc6 {Black is asking us to oblige and open the diagonal for the a7-bishop with d4-d5.} 
15. Ra3
15. Qe7
16. d5 {We do not mind opening up the a7-g1 diagonal as we will exchange the dark-squared bishops soon with Nc4 and Be3. The black queen cannot reach the queenside easily and we have free rein on the queenside.} 
16. Bd7
17. Nc4 {We will go Be3 and exchange the active bishop. The knight on e3 is also eyeing the f5-square. Our plan will be to go b4 and eventually break with c5.} 
