9. Ne7 {Black wants to regroup his knight to g6 and will aim to play c6, d5 in the center. This has a lot of similarities to the Bb6 chapter which evolved from this system. I have played this in several games in the past with the Black pieces. The drawback of this system is that Black allows us to take control of the center easily. Our ideal setup would be to play d4, Bd3/ b3-c2, Nd2-f1-g3 and Be3. At the same time we need to always be ready to deal with the d5 break.} 
10. d4 {Given the chance, we go for the d4 break immediately. This is one of the reasons why many players go for h6 first. They play Ne7 only after Nbd2 when d4 is not as effective.} 
10. Ng6
11. Nbd2
11. c6 {This is a critical position. Black is ready to take on d4 and go for either direct d5 or Ne4, followed by d5. We have a few different options here.} 
12. Bd3 {This is my main recommendation. We overprotect the important e4-pawn. Now that our bishop is already on the b1-h7 diagonal, Black cannot just take on d4 and go d5. Our plan is similar to Bb3- go for Bc2 followed by Nf1. I faced this myself, in one of my favourite wins, against a strong GM to score my final GM norm although I was Black in that game.} 
12. exd4 {I had only recently started playing this system with Black and this was one of the first ideas which I learned from the Black side (albeit in a different position with the bishop on b3). I was really happy to play this over the board immediately at my next event. Being young and confident does have its benefits :)} 
13. cxd4
13. d5
14. e5 {We are always happy to get this structure, especially with the bishop already in the b1-h7 diagonal.} 
14. Nh5 {I would recommend you to spend time here (maybe at least a couple of minutes) to get a feel of the position and find the strong continuation which my opponent missed.} 
15. g3
15. Bxh3
16. Nf1 {We are threatening to go Ng5 or even N3h2, winning the piece on h5. Black has to somehow try to muddy the waters.} 
16. f6
17. Nh4
17. Nxg3 {A very creative resource. Try to figure out what we should do with White.} 
18. Nxg6
18. hxg6
19. Qf3 {This is a beautiful move, saying no to the piece on g3. We want to bring the queen into the game!} 
19. Bxf1
20. Bxg6 {And we will finally take the poor knight on g3 next and continue the attack on the kingside.} 
