[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Bc5
5. c3
5. d6
6. O-O
6. a6
7. a4
7. Ba7
8. Re1
8. O-O
9. h3
9. Ne7 {Black wants to regroup his knight to g6 and will aim to play c6, d5 in the center. This has a lot of similarities to the Bb6 chapter which evolved from this system. I have played this in several games in the past with the Black pieces. The drawback of this system is that Black allows us to take control of the center easily. Our ideal setup would be to play d4, Bd3/ b3-c2, Nd2-f1-g3 and Be3. At the same time we need to always be ready to deal with the d5 break.} 
10. d4 {Given the chance, we go for the d4 break immediately. This is one of the reasons why many players go for h6 first. They play Ne7 only after Nbd2 when d4 is not as effective.} 
10. Ng6
11. Nbd2
11. c6 {This is a critical position. Black is ready to take on d4 and go for either direct d5 or Ne4, followed by d5. We have a few different options here.} 
12. Ba2 {This is a very interesting move which was played by Praggnanandhaa against yours truly in a crucial game in the World Youth 2019. It has an insanely deep idea that I was pretty shocked to hear about after the game. At that point for me, it was a total eye-opener regarding the preparation that goes on behind the scenes, to become a very strong player. I am pretty sure you guys will also agree with me after you see the following line.} 
12. exd4 {This is the top choice of the computer and the easiest way to equalize against the move 12.Bb3. I had even played this idea in a game previously. So young Pragg was curious to see if there would be any change after the move 12.Ba2.} 
13. cxd4
13. d5
14. e5
14. Nh5
15. Bb1 {We bring the bishop to the important diagonal and we will continue with Nf1 next.} 
15. Nhf4
16. Nf1
16. f6
17. Ra3 {We have seen this before- we bring the rook along the third rank.} 
17. fxe5
18. Nxe5 {We will go for Rf3 next.} 
18. Bf5 {This would have equalized had White gone for 12.Bb3 and subsequently 15.Bc2. Can you understand the point now?} 
19. Bxf4
19. Bxb1
20. Bg3 {This was the point of his preparation. If the bishop was on c2 in the same line, White would have been forced to take on c2 with the queen and Black would have been able to equalize after Nf4. This was pretty surreal for me at that time. Still, I am not recommending this as the main line as there are a couple of ways for Black to equalize. But it is a very good surprise weapon even against very strong opposition.} 
