9. h6 {This is very popular as it occurs via many different move orders. Many Black players go for h6 early to avoid Bg5. h6 is a useful move in the lines involving Re8 and Be6 which is the main line at the top level. In fxe6 structures, it is not that important, but Black has no other useful waiting move in this position. So mostly, Black goes for it as he wants White to commit with Nbd2 after which direct Be3 or d4 is not possible.} 
10. Nbd2
10. Be6 {There have been a lot of top-level games in this line in the past but its popularity has reduced a lot over the last few years. It has almost been concluded that White is slightly better in the resulting positions and Black has to defend passively. His hopes of a kingside attack never really materialize.} 
11. Bxe6
11. fxe6
12. b4 {We gain space on the queenside and at the same time, we create a potential threat of b4-b5. Let us go through some general rules for this middlegame.   1) We will first secure our kingside- our next moves are likely to be a variation of Nf1, Ra2, g3, and N1h2. Only after we fully secure our kingside do we start our play on the queenside by preparing b5 or d4.   2) We will aim to exchange one pair of minor pieces- either by going Be3 or by exchanging our bishop for one of the Black knights (usually on f4).   3) I like to take on f4 with our bishop mainly when Black is forced to recapture with the queen. The queen on f4 is usually badly placed and has to retreat soon.   4) Our ideal setup on the kingside would be to get g3, Kg2, and Nf1-h2. This is perfect since it is extremely hard to create any attack for Black and at the same time, our pieces are not passive. The knight can jump to g4 at any moment.} 
12. Qe8
13. Nf1
13. Qf7 {This happened in my Titled Tuesday game against Tania, S. I had our plan clearly in my mind and ended up getting a big advantage.} 
14. Ra2 {A very useful move, keeping an eye on f2 and at the same time, it can become active via the 2nd rank- for instance, with d4 and Rd2. Also, another point is that now b5 is always possible without having to worry about axb5 and Bxf2 tricks.} 
14. Ne7
15. N1h2 {We first protect our f3-knight before going for g3 and Kg2.} 
15. Ng6
16. g3
16. c6
17. Kg2 {And I had a good edge which I later converted (with a lot of mistakes in a typical blitz game- I only vouch for the opening part :))} 
