11. Bxe6
11. fxe6
12. b4 {We gain space on the queenside and at the same time, we create a potential threat of b4-b5. Let us go through some general rules for this middlegame.   1) We will first secure our kingside- our next moves are likely to be a variation of Nf1, Ra2, g3, and N1h2. Only after we fully secure our kingside do we start our play on the queenside by preparing b5 or d4.   2) We will aim to exchange one pair of minor pieces- either by going Be3 or by exchanging our bishop for one of the Black knights (usually on f4).   3) I like to take on f4 with our bishop mainly when Black is forced to recapture with the queen. The queen on f4 is usually badly placed and has to retreat soon.   4) Our ideal setup on the kingside would be to get g3, Kg2, and Nf1-h2. This is perfect since it is extremely hard to create any attack for Black and at the same time, our pieces are not passive. The knight can jump to g4 at any moment.} 
12. Ne7 {Black wants to bring his c6-knight to g6 and then go for Nh5-f4. This way he also sidesteps a potential b5. Here, in that case, we do not take on f4 and instead usually continue with Be3 and d4 plans. Both the knights end up fighting for the one square on f4. So we can spend a couple of moves to kick him off with g2-g3 (for instance Kh1, Ng1).} 
13. Nf1
