[White "14) Italian 4...Bc5 5.c3 - Modern Be6"]
[Black "Italian 4...Bc5 - Modern Be6 without h6"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Bc5
5. c3
5. d6
6. O-O
6. a6
7. a4
7. Ba7
8. Re1
8. O-O
9. h3
9. Re8 {Black does not want to waste a tempo with h6. In most of these lines, it is necessary but there is one particular interesting sequence for Black.} 
10. Nbd2
10. Be6
11. Bxe6 {We always take, forcing the rook to e6. It has two reasons- 1) The rook is not ideal on e6 for Black as it will come under pressure after the d4 break. 2) If Black takes on c4 the knight is also not ideal there for us, as Black would go for the immediate d5.} 
11. Rxe6
12. b4 {Our standard reaction after the trade on e6. We gain space and create a potential idea of b5.} 
12. d5 {Black can get in move d5 but we simply maintain the tension in the center. We let him decide what he wants to do with his center.} 
13. Qc2
13. d4
14. Nb3 {The knight is perfect here keeping an eye on the d4-square and also ready to jump to c5 in the future.} 
14. dxc3
15. Qxc3
15. Rd6
16. Qc4 {This is a very clever move making sure that Rxd3 does not come with a tempo. We want to go b5 or Be3 next. So Black has to take the gauntlet with Rxd3.} 
16. Rxd3
17. b5
17. Rxf3 {Only move. Black gives up an exchange to weaken our kingside. But he still does not have a direct attack against our king.} 
18. gxf3
18. Nd4
19. Nxd4
19. Bxd4
20. Ra2 {Black has only one pawn as compensation for the missing exchange. The engines claim that Black is fine with slow play such as h6 or Nd7. I feel practically Black is under pressure to prove it while we have an easy game. We can go Kh2 and maybe create some initiative along the 'g' file.} 
