8. O-O
9. h3
9. h6 {Black players usually start with this move, before going for Re8 and Be6. It is a useful waiting move to force White to go Nbd2 and also stop a potential Bg5 or Ng5.} 
10. Nbd2
10. Re8 {This is one of the most common and critical lines at the top level in the Italian. Black is extremely solid and does not want to make any unnecessary weaknesses by directly going Be6. His aim is usually to go Be6 next and recapture with the rook, followed by an eventual d5.} 
11. b4 {Once Black has played Re8 we can go for b4 as it is clear that he should likely go for the Be6 plan. Always go for the most necessary move first and b4 is the most useful move here for White.} 
11. Be6
12. Bxe6 {As usual we always trade on e6 forcing the rook to a shaky square. It does have its benefits for Black as he can play d5 and Rd6 quickly.} 
12. Rxe6
13. Qc2 {I really like this move and it is one of the reasons behind the revival and popularity of the Italian. The queen on c2 is very flexible and we are keeping our options open regarding our minor pieces. If Black decides to go Ne7-g6 we will also do the same with Nf1-g3. d5 here is not so good as we can quickly start our play on the queenside with our minor pieces. In addition, d5 and dxe4 will not exchange queens anymore.} 
13. d5 {Is the most natural move for most people. I have seen this being played many times when Black is not well prepared and starts thinking over the board. The problem is that Black cannot hold on to the center easily as we will quickly go b5 and c4. It would be different if he was in time to go Qd7 and Rd8.} 
14. Nb3 {We want to go b5 and c4 next forcing Black to release the tension in the center.} 
14. Nh5 {Black immediately tries to start something on the kingside but his center comes under fire.} 
15. b5
15. Ne7
16. exd5
16. Nxd5
17. Nxe5 {The general rule from the book 'My System', always comes to my mind in these situations. Take any central pawn if it can be done without too much danger. We should not be afraid to go for the critical continuations in these positions.} 
17. Qe8
18. d4
18. f6 {Black looks like he is winning a piece but the d5-knight is also in trouble.} 
19. c4
19. Nb4
20. Qc3 {We will win the b4-knight and Black is left with a weak pawn on d4 at the end.} 
