13. Qc2 {I really like this move and it is one of the reasons behind the revival and popularity of the Italian. The queen on c2 is very flexible and we are keeping our options open regarding our minor pieces. If Black decides to go Ne7-g6 we will also do the same with Nf1-g3. d5 here is not so good as we can quickly start our play on the queenside with our minor pieces. In addition, d5 and dxe4 will not exchange queens anymore.} 
13. Ne7 {Black decides to immediately bring his knight to g6. This works well against the Bb2 system, but here we still have our bishop on c1 keeping an eye on f4. As we saw in the previous variations, c4 becomes a common idea when Black removes his knight from c6.} 
14. Nf1 {We also copy Black by bringing our knight to g3. However, the drawback of this move is that now the d5 break becomes more effective. The knight can no longer jump to b3.} 
