14. b5 {The most popular move, stopping our queenside play with b5 and c4. On the other hand, it does create a potential weakness for us on the queenside and we can decide whether we want to keep the 'a' file open or closed.} 
15. Ra1 {We have two plans here. One is to go Nb3 next followed by Bd2 and c4. In case Black goes for d5 we can also go for Be3 to exploit the weakness on c5. Black usually tries to go for Nh5-f4 and Rf6. We will try to meet Nh5 with Nh4. The other plan is to go for our usual Nf1-g3-f5 and create play on the kingside.} 
15. Rd8 {We have to decide which way to go with our knight. With the rook on d8, the d5 plan is quite effective once we go Nf1.} 
16. Nb3 {We keep an eye on c5, discouraging d5. Black's other plan is to go for Nh5 and play on the kingside. Let's see how both of them work.} 
16. Bb6 {This is the most played move. The bishop was pretty awkward on a7, hanging in some of the lines. Now Black wants to go Nh5 next. A lot of moves have been played here.} 
17. a5 {I like to gain this tempo when possible, and then exchange off the bishops. This will stop d5 for the foreseeable future and both sides will concentrate on the kingside.} 
17. Ba7
18. Be3
18. Bxe3
19. Rxe3
19. Nh5 {Once the knight reaches f4 it is quite difficult to get rid of him. There are two approaches here. One is to let him stay on f4 and the other is to immediately dislodge him.} 
20. Nh4 {Given the chance we will go g3 next and restrict the knight on h5 but Black is quick to stop it.} 
20. Rf6
21. Kh2 {Again we want g3.} 
21. Nf4
22. Rd1
