[Black "Italian 4...Bc5 - Modern Be6 13...Qd7 14...b5  #12"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Nf6
4. d3
4. Bc5
5. c3
5. d6
6. O-O
6. a6
7. a4
7. Ba7
8. Re1
8. O-O
9. h3
9. h6 {Black players usually start with this move, before going for Re8 and Be6. It is a useful waiting move to force White to go Nbd2 and also stop a potential Bg5 or Ng5.} 
10. Nbd2
10. Re8 {This is one of the most common and critical lines at the top level in the Italian. Black is extremely solid and does not want to make any unnecessary weaknesses by directly going Be6. His aim is usually to go Be6 next and recapture with the rook, followed by an eventual d5.} 
11. b4 {Once Black has played Re8 we can go for b4 as it is clear that he should likely go for the Be6 plan. Always go for the most necessary move first and b4 is the most useful move here for White.} 
11. Be6
12. Bxe6 {As usual we always trade on e6 forcing the rook to a shaky square. It does have its benefits for Black as he can play d5 and Rd6 quickly.} 
12. Rxe6
13. Qc2 {I really like this move and it is one of the reasons behind the revival and popularity of the Italian. The queen on c2 is very flexible and we are keeping our options open regarding our minor pieces. If Black decides to go Ne7-g6 we will also do the same with Nf1-g3. d5 here is not so good as we can quickly start our play on the queenside with our minor pieces. In addition, d5 and dxe4 will not exchange queens anymore.} 
13. Qd7 {The main move in the position. Black also makes a useful move, waiting for us to commit to a plan. We are in a bit of a dilemma here as we do not want to allow d5 and at the same time, we have to have some kind of a plan.} 
14. Rb1 {A cunning waiting move which we have seen in a previous variation. Here we stop the move d5 and also create threats such as b5 and c4.} 
14. b5 {The most popular move, stopping our queenside play with b5 and c4. On the other hand, it does create a potential weakness for us on the queenside and we can decide whether we want to keep the 'a' file open or closed.} 
15. Ra1 {We have two plans here. One is to go Nb3 next followed by Bd2 and c4. In case Black goes for d5 we can also go for Be3 to exploit the weakness on c5. Black usually tries to go for Nh5-f4 and Rf6. We will try to meet Nh5 with Nh4. The other plan is to go for our usual Nf1-g3-f5 and create play on the kingside.} 
15. Ree8 {The most played move. Black connects the rooks and also gets out of the way of potential d4 ideas from White. He could go Ne7-g6 next especially after Nb3.} 
16. Nf1 {Now we get our knight to the kingside. It is more effective once Black has gone back Re8 and d5 is no longer as threatening.} 
16. d5
17. Ng3
17. Rad8
18. Bd2 {Ideally our plan next would be to go Qc1, Nf5 and Bxh6 in some order, but the problem is that the f5-square is unstable and Black can take twice on e4 when we go for Nf5 and Qc1. So we have to be clever about it. As long as the queen is on c2 we can go for Nf5 without having to worry about any tactics.} 
18. Qe6 {The queen is perfect here keeping an eye on the kingside and also on the c4-square as we will see in some of the lines.} 
19. Nf5
19. Kh8 {This is clever, getting out of the way of Bxh6 ideas. It is pretty frustrating for us that we cannot go Qc1 and Bxh6 due to the shaky knight on f5.} 
20. g4 {Maybe not objectively the best move according to computers but the most practical and dangerous one. It firmly cements our knight on f5.} 
20. dxe4
21. dxe4
21. Qc4 {All this happened in a top-level game between Dominguez and So in 2021. Black is threatening quite a few ideas and it is time for us to exchange the queens. The knight on f5 still gives us some edge in the position.} 
22. Qa2
22. Qxa2
23. Rxa2
23. Rd3
24. Kg2 {One of Black's main issues is his bishop on a7 which is stuck on the queenside. We can even close the queenside with a5 further restricting the bishop. Black got desperate in the aforementioned game and was lost in a few moves.} 
24. h5
25. g5
25. Ng8 {1/2-1/2 (65) Dominguez Perez,L (2758)-So,W (2772) Saint Louis 2021} 
26. c4 {We are simply winning here. One of the rooks will gain control over the 'c' file and the queenside is falling.} 
