6. Bg5 {This is the main line in the position. We want to try and exploit the move a6, which is a non-developing move in the corner of the board. Our idea is to go Nd5 next. Initially, I was hesitant to just go for the most played moves. But then I had a game against Aryan Tari (2650 GM and a well-known opening theoretician) in the El Llobregat Open 2022 in this particular line. He was not familiar with the details, and I ended up getting more than an hour advantage on the clock with a better position. We will see that game, but it shows that the Nc3-line is still vastly unexplored, and we can catch most of our opponents off guard.} 
6. h6 {The standard reaction to Bg5.} 
7. Bxf6
7. Qxf6
8. Nd5 {This is the point of Bg5. We will try to keep our knight on d5 for as long as possible and go for the d4 break.} 
8. Qd8
9. c3 {Black has to decide how he wants to react to the move d4.} 
9. O-O {This is much less common as Black will be forced to give up the center. However, we need to understand how to utilize it. Black does have the bishop pair.} 
10. d4
10. Ba7 {Black is ready to give up the e5-pawn in return for development and the bishop pair. It has been played in only one old game.} 
11. Nxe5
11. Nxe5
12. dxe5
12. c6
13. Nf4
13. Re8
14. Qf3 {We put more pressure on the f7-square and also prepare O-O-O in the future.} 
14. d5
15. O-O-O {This is the top choice of Leela. White actually gives up an exchange after-} 
15. Qh4
16. exd5 {The center is more valuable here than the exchange. We get opposite colour bishops on the board and our attacking chances are much higher. Also, we are getting two pawns for the exchange.} 
16. Bg4
17. Qe4
17. Bxd1
18. Kxd1 {We are completely okay with our king on d1 as there is no way for Black to attack it.} 
18. cxd5
19. Bxd5 {We are threatening to take on f7 next. The bishop is a monster on d5 keeping an eye on the whole board. Is it not worth the exchange?} 
19. Rad8
20. g3
20. Qe7
21. Re1 {And we have tremendous compensation for the exchange. Maybe Black can hold the balance but it is never easy in a practical game.} 
