5. Nc3 {We are moving on to a more aggressive and dynamic version of the Italian that has not been deeply explored yet. We are developing our pieces faster than in the previous variations. The positions are quite symmetrical, and this increases the value of tempo for both sides. There are three major ideas here for us: go for Be3 and open the 'f' file for our rook, to go for a quick Bg5, and to meet d6 with Na4 winning the bishop pair.} 
5. a6
6. Bg5 {This is the main line in the position. We want to try and exploit the move a6, which is a non-developing move in the corner of the board. Our idea is to go Nd5 next. Initially, I was hesitant to just go for the most played moves. But then I had a game against Aryan Tari (2650 GM and a well-known opening theoretician) in the El Llobregat Open 2022 in this particular line. He was not familiar with the details, and I ended up getting more than an hour advantage on the clock with a better position. We will see that game, but it shows that the Nc3-line is still vastly unexplored, and we can catch most of our opponents off guard.} 
6. h6 {The standard reaction to Bg5.} 
7. Bxf6
7. Qxf6
8. Nd5 {This is the point of Bg5. We will try to keep our knight on d5 for as long as possible and go for the d4 break.} 
8. Qd8
9. c3 {Black has to decide how he wants to react to the move d4.} 
9. d6 {The most natural move strengthening the center.} 
10. d4
10. Ba7 {This is the move I would expect to happen in most of the games. Black maintains the tension in the center. Surprisingly Black has to play very accurately for the next 10 moves.} 
11. dxe5 {Already Black has to make a very important decision. In my game against Aryan Tari, he spent more than half an hour on this decision.} 
11. Nxe5 {This happened in my game and it is something that I expect only from either a strong player or someone who does not calculate much. This is because we have the option to win the pawn on e5 by force and Black has to be able to evaluate the resulting position correctly. With this move, Black is ready to play c6 next, kicking the knight out from the d5-square.} 
12. Nxe5
12. dxe5
13. Qh5 {There is no way for Black to defend the e5-pawn. Another threat is the move Nb6 as f7 is hanging.} 
13. O-O
14. Qxe5
14. Re8
15. Qf4 {This is the position that Black had to evaluate correctly. There is only one move to maintain equality.} 
15. Qd6 {Black can win back the pawn in a very clever fashion.} 
16. Qxd6
16. Rxe4+ {The point- intermediate check! Black is not out of the woods yet though.} 
17. Ne3
17. cxd6
18. Bd5
18. Re7 {The most accurate move preparing to move the c8-bishop.} 
19. O-O-O {All of this happened in my game with Aryan Tari. So far he had played very slowly and correctly but here he slipped up.} 
19. Bxe3+ {This was accompanied by a draw offer. But I knew that this was inaccurate and White gets a small edge.} 
20. fxe3
20. Be6
21. Bf3 {This is the point- we can preserve the bishops on the board! There are a few major reasons why White has a small edge here-   1) The pawn on d6 is a clear weakness to attack. Black is forced to defend it passively.   2) The pawn on e3 however is not an easy target and can be easily defended by the king on c1. Moreover, Black is usually forced to defend his pawn first.   3) The bishop is perfect on f3 keeping an eye on the weak queenside pawns.} 
21. Rd8
22. a4 {The best way to protect the a2-pawn. Surprisingly it is very important to keep the c3-pawn protected as otherwise, it runs into Bf5-e4 as in my game. I was hesitant about this during the game due to the move a5 which makes our move look very anti-positional- fixing our pawns on light squares. However, chess is a concrete game and concretely it is more essential for White to regroup his pieces effectively- with Rd4 and Rd1.} 
22. a5
23. Rd4
23. Kf8
24. Rhd1
24. Red7
25. Bd5 {We will see this endgame in more detail in the model games section- ½-½ (43) Safarli, E (2579) -Santos Latasa,J (2633) Castelldefels 2021.} 
