[Black "Carlsen, M. vs. So, W., Sinquefield Cup 2019"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {One of my favourite games of Magnus. It perfectly showcases why he is called an endgame genius.} 1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4
3. Bc5
4. O-O
4. Nf6
5. d3
5. O-O
6. c3
6. d6
7. h3
7. h6
8. Re1
8. a6
9. a4
9. a5 {This is a clever line which posed me a lot of problems during the course and also during my general preparation. Black has wasted a tempo playing a6-a5 but he has forced White to go a4 stopping the usual Bb5-a4.} 
10. Nbd2
10. Be6
11. Bb5
11. Na7
12. d4
12. Nxb5
13. dxc5
13. Na7
14. b3 {White wants to get his bishop to a3 next.} 
14. Re8
15. cxd6
15. Qxd6
16. Ba3
16. c5 {Black has managed to equalize according to computers. This is where the genius of Magnus comes in.} 
17. Nc4 {White willingly doubles his pawns on the queenside and also exchanges one of his knights. It is not clear how to evaluate the resulting position- The b7-pawn is a weakness for Black but it is compensated by our c4-pawn. It all comes down to who is faster and better in regrouping their pieces to ideal squares.} 
17. Qxd1
18. Raxd1
18. Bxc4
19. bxc4 {This does look very anti-positional at first sight but it is similar to the classic game -Portisch - Fischer. White claims that the doubled pawns actually help him control some key squares (d4 and b4) and create a weakness on the semi open 'b' file.} 
19. b6 {This is a natural move but also an innacuracy as it creates a clear weakness for us to attack.} 
20. Nh4
20. Rad8
21. f3 {We want to go Nf5 and Ne3.} 
21. g6
22. g3 {We go the other way now.} 
22. Nh5
23. Kf2
23. Nc6
24. Bc1
24. Kg7
25. Be3 {The bishop is well placed here, keeping an eye on both the sides of the board.} 
25. Rxd1
26. Rxd1
26. Rd8 {This is useless as Black has no play on the 'd' file.} 
27. Rb1 {The d-file is useless. The main weakness for Black is the b6-pawn. It is clear now that White is better, but chess is not that easy. White needs to create another weakness in order to breakthrough.} 
27. Rb8
28. Ng2
28. Nf6
29. Ke2
29. Ne8
30. Bf2 {The knight is finally going to d5.} 
30. Nd6
31. Ne3
31. Ne7 {The key mistake in the game. It looks extremely natural to stop the move Nd5 but it turns out the exchange on d5 is just winning for White.} 
